WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.273 --> 00:00:09.152
You know. I can now bite
my fingernails so evenly

2
00:00:09.176 --> 00:00:11.388
that I don't even need
to use a clipper anymore.

3
00:00:11.412 --> 00:00:12.956
But it's a pleasure
to use clippers.

4
00:00:12.980 --> 00:00:14.824
Why gnaw away
like a mental patient

5
00:00:14.848 --> 00:00:16.448
when we have
this elegant device?

6
00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:21.598
What if you're in prison?

7
00:00:21.622 --> 00:00:22.966
They don't give you clippers?

8
00:00:22.990 --> 00:00:24.501
No. it's like a weapon.

9
00:00:24.525 --> 00:00:26.970
You know what's really a
weapon? That big toenail.

10
00:00:26.994 --> 00:00:28.271
You let that grow for a month.

11
00:00:28.295 --> 00:00:30.529
take it in the
shower. it's like a shiv.

12
00:00:32.433 --> 00:00:33.910
I love prison.

13
00:00:33.934 --> 00:00:36.313
It is fascinating.

14
00:00:36.337 --> 00:00:38.681
Yeah... maybe someday.

15
00:00:45.479 --> 00:00:48.458
You want me to find
a poem about Susan?

16
00:00:48.482 --> 00:00:51.061
May she rest in peace.

17
00:00:51.085 --> 00:00:52.662
Well. we think it
would be a nice touch

18
00:00:52.686 --> 00:00:55.332
for the foundation literature.

19
00:00:55.356 --> 00:00:57.156
You have a favorite
poet. George?

20
00:00:59.093 --> 00:01:01.826
I like. uh. Flavman.

21
00:01:03.097 --> 00:01:04.874
Pardon?

22
00:01:04.898 --> 00:01:06.976
Flavman.

23
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.347
Well. you should choose the
poem since you knew Susan best

24
00:01:10.371 --> 00:01:12.615
at the time of
her unfortunate...

25
00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:14.351
Ahem... accident.

26
00:01:18.412 --> 00:01:19.689
He cleared his throat?

27
00:01:19.713 --> 00:01:21.491
Yes. So?

28
00:01:21.515 --> 00:01:25.762
He did it right as he said.
"Her unfortunate accident."

29
00:01:25.786 --> 00:01:28.231
Not getting it.
Jerry. a throat clear

30
00:01:28.255 --> 00:01:30.067
is a non-verbal
implication of doubt.

31
00:01:30.091 --> 00:01:31.668
He thinks I killed Susan.

32
00:01:31.692 --> 00:01:33.158
Oh. help me. Rhonda.

33
00:01:36.097 --> 00:01:37.074
What time is it?

34
00:01:37.098 --> 00:01:38.341
One-fifteen.

35
00:01:38.365 --> 00:01:39.365
Right now?

36
00:01:40.401 --> 00:01:42.679
I gotta go meet Pam.

37
00:01:42.703 --> 00:01:44.681
Oh. the bookstore
girl. How's that going?

38
00:01:44.705 --> 00:01:45.682
Okay.

39
00:01:45.706 --> 00:01:47.517
I'm just not gaga over her.

40
00:01:47.541 --> 00:01:49.186
For once. I'd like to be gaga.

41
00:01:49.210 --> 00:01:50.587
Where's Elaine?

42
00:01:50.611 --> 00:01:52.456
She's having Carol.
Gail and Lisa over.

43
00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:54.091
You know. they
all have kids now.

44
00:01:54.115 --> 00:01:56.126
What's with all these
people having babies?

45
00:01:56.150 --> 00:01:58.695
Perpetuation of the
species. Yeah. right.

46
00:01:58.719 --> 00:02:00.363
By the way. just
for the record...

47
00:02:00.387 --> 00:02:01.764
No. I did not!

48
00:02:01.788 --> 00:02:02.788
All right.

49
00:02:04.125 --> 00:02:05.469
But because it comes out

50
00:02:05.493 --> 00:02:08.393
of your baby. it smells good.

51
00:02:09.597 --> 00:02:12.542
Well. that's... That's sweet.

52
00:02:12.566 --> 00:02:15.878
Being a mother has
made me feel so beautiful.

53
00:02:15.902 --> 00:02:20.172
Elaine. ya gotta have a baby.

54
00:02:21.175 --> 00:02:22.852
Oh. hey. you know.

55
00:02:22.876 --> 00:02:24.454
I had a piece of whitefish

56
00:02:24.478 --> 00:02:27.290
over at Barney Greengrass
the other day. and I...

57
00:02:27.314 --> 00:02:31.161
Elaine. move to Long Island
and have a baby already.

58
00:02:31.185 --> 00:02:34.431
I really like the city.
The city's a toilet.

59
00:02:34.455 --> 00:02:36.733
When's the last time
you saw my little Adam?

60
00:02:36.757 --> 00:02:38.668
Uh. it was in the Hamptons.

61
00:02:38.692 --> 00:02:41.338
Ah. I have pictures. Oh.
no. no. that's okay. It's...

62
00:02:41.362 --> 00:02:43.362
Look at him. just look at him.

63
00:02:46.534 --> 00:02:47.744
So Elaine was telling me

64
00:02:47.768 --> 00:02:49.946
about this piece of whitefish
she had the other day.

65
00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:52.215
Do you really think I'm
wrong about this Wyck guy?

66
00:02:52.239 --> 00:02:54.017
You know. if you really
wanna test him out.

67
00:02:54.041 --> 00:02:55.852
why don't you try
the Jerry Lewis trick?

68
00:02:55.876 --> 00:02:56.919
Jerry Lewis?

69
00:02:56.943 --> 00:02:58.955
I heard when Jerry
Lewis left a meeting

70
00:02:58.979 --> 00:03:01.591
he'd purposely leave a
briefcase with a tape recorder in it.

71
00:03:01.615 --> 00:03:03.593
Then after five minutes.
he'd come back for it.

72
00:03:03.617 --> 00:03:05.295
listen to what everyone
said about him.

73
00:03:05.319 --> 00:03:07.063
That's pretty
paranoid. Yes. it is.

74
00:03:07.087 --> 00:03:08.465
I like it! I thought you might.

75
00:03:11.192 --> 00:03:12.536
Oh. Hi.

76
00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:13.870
I'm Pam.

77
00:03:13.894 --> 00:03:15.126
You must be Kramer.

78
00:03:16.797 --> 00:03:18.975
Jerry has. uh. told
me a lot about you.

79
00:03:21.302 --> 00:03:23.713
Well. uh. I'm
supposed to meet Jerry.

80
00:03:23.737 --> 00:03:24.947
It's my day off.

81
00:03:24.971 --> 00:03:26.783
I work in a bookstore.

82
00:03:26.807 --> 00:03:28.973
Books.

83
00:03:30.578 --> 00:03:32.077
Oh! Careful!

84
00:03:34.781 --> 00:03:36.693
Hi. Sorry I'm late. Hi.

85
00:03:36.717 --> 00:03:37.994
That's okay. Kramer let me in.

86
00:03:38.018 --> 00:03:39.796
If we rush. we can
still make the movie.

87
00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:41.086
It was really nice meeting you.

88
00:03:49.597 --> 00:03:50.973
I'm in trouble. buddy.

89
00:03:50.997 --> 00:03:52.475
I just met a woman.

90
00:03:52.499 --> 00:03:54.539
Go on. Well...

91
00:03:55.369 --> 00:03:57.214
she's Jerry's girlfriend.

92
00:03:57.238 --> 00:03:58.515
Ah. yes.

93
00:03:58.539 --> 00:03:59.749
forbidden love.

94
00:03:59.773 --> 00:04:01.718
She works in a bookshop.

95
00:04:01.742 --> 00:04:02.985
Her name is Pam.

96
00:04:03.009 --> 00:04:04.487
Pam.

97
00:04:04.511 --> 00:04:06.831
I don't know the woman.
but she sounds quite fetching.

98
00:04:08.014 --> 00:04:10.527
I can't even speak
in front of her.

99
00:04:10.551 --> 00:04:11.828
Jerry!

100
00:04:11.852 --> 00:04:14.130
What could she
possibly see in Jerry?

101
00:04:14.154 --> 00:04:15.154
Oh!

102
00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:18.668
She has delicate beauty.

103
00:04:18.692 --> 00:04:19.969
Jerry wouldn't know delicate

104
00:04:19.993 --> 00:04:21.738
if it bludgeoned
him over the head.

105
00:04:21.762 --> 00:04:24.741
And yet. he's my friend.

106
00:04:24.765 --> 00:04:27.009
And therein lies the tragedy.

107
00:04:27.033 --> 00:04:30.213
For I believe. sadly for you.

108
00:04:30.237 --> 00:04:33.617
that there is but one
woman meant for each of us.

109
00:04:33.641 --> 00:04:35.318
One perfect angel

110
00:04:35.342 --> 00:04:37.186
for whom we are
put on this earth.

111
00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:38.755
Oh. that's beautiful. Newman.

112
00:04:38.779 --> 00:04:40.823
One winsome tulip

113
00:04:40.847 --> 00:04:42.792
we ceaselessly yearn for

114
00:04:42.816 --> 00:04:45.962
throughout our
dreary workaday lives.

115
00:04:45.986 --> 00:04:50.133
and you. my friend.
have found your angel.

116
00:04:50.157 --> 00:04:51.901
I can tell.

117
00:04:51.925 --> 00:04:53.970
For my heart has
also been captured

118
00:04:53.994 --> 00:04:55.872
by a breathless beauty

119
00:04:55.896 --> 00:04:58.575
whom I fear I will
never possess.

120
00:04:58.599 --> 00:05:00.644
I thought we were
talking about me.

121
00:05:00.668 --> 00:05:02.712
Oh. right.

122
00:05:02.736 --> 00:05:04.714
Kramer. you have
to confront Jerry.

123
00:05:04.738 --> 00:05:06.483
Confront Jerry? I can't.

124
00:05:06.507 --> 00:05:07.584
You must. I won't.

125
00:05:07.608 --> 00:05:09.252
You will!

126
00:05:09.276 --> 00:05:12.756
"Elaine. you gotta have a baby."

127
00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:14.223
Ehh.

128
00:05:14.247 --> 00:05:15.925
Where are the poetry magazines?

129
00:05:15.949 --> 00:05:17.727
<i>The New Yorker</i> has poetry.

130
00:05:17.751 --> 00:05:20.129
Yes.<i> The New Yorker.</i>

131
00:05:20.153 --> 00:05:21.731
Why do you invite
these women over

132
00:05:21.755 --> 00:05:23.065
if they annoy you so much?

133
00:05:23.089 --> 00:05:24.467
Well. they're my friends.

134
00:05:24.491 --> 00:05:27.904
but they act as if having a
baby takes some kind of talent.

135
00:05:27.928 --> 00:05:29.773
Come on. You wanna have a baby.

136
00:05:29.797 --> 00:05:31.908
Why? Because I can?

137
00:05:31.932 --> 00:05:33.276
It's the life force.

138
00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:35.244
I saw a show on
the mollusk last night.

139
00:05:35.268 --> 00:05:38.247
Elaine. the mollusk
travels from Alaska to Chile

140
00:05:38.271 --> 00:05:39.849
just for a shot at
another mollusk.

141
00:05:39.873 --> 00:05:41.250
You think you're any better?

142
00:05:41.274 --> 00:05:44.654
Yes. I think I am
better than the mollusk.

143
00:05:44.678 --> 00:05:46.389
Excuse me. I couldn't
help overhearing

144
00:05:46.413 --> 00:05:48.325
what you were
saying. Oh. I'm sorry...

145
00:05:48.349 --> 00:05:50.159
No. no. I think I
agree with you.

146
00:05:50.183 --> 00:05:52.696
I mean. all this talk
about having babies.

147
00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:54.497
Yeah. like you must procreate.

148
00:05:54.521 --> 00:05:56.333
Besides. anyone can do it.

149
00:05:56.357 --> 00:05:57.567
Oh. it's been done to death.

150
00:06:00.927 --> 00:06:03.373
I. uh. should have a
poem very soon now.

151
00:06:03.397 --> 00:06:05.742
Are you okay. George?

152
00:06:05.766 --> 00:06:07.176
No. no.

153
00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:08.700
Not really.

154
00:06:10.871 --> 00:06:16.786
Ever since Susan passed
on I have good days and bad.

155
00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:21.090
Some days I... I'm
haunted by one word:

156
00:06:21.114 --> 00:06:22.892
why?

157
00:06:22.916 --> 00:06:25.562
Why Susan?

158
00:06:25.586 --> 00:06:29.833
Why wasn't it me
licking those invitations?

159
00:06:29.857 --> 00:06:31.923
Why am I still here?

160
00:06:33.394 --> 00:06:35.494
But I gotta run. uh...

161
00:06:43.236 --> 00:06:44.481
Now. the stock options

162
00:06:44.505 --> 00:06:46.371
for this year look. uh. quite...

163
00:06:54.347 --> 00:06:56.058
Briefcase.

164
00:06:59.352 --> 00:07:02.231
So. Kevin. if I
don't want children.

165
00:07:02.255 --> 00:07:04.567
does that make me
a bad humanitarian?

166
00:07:04.591 --> 00:07:05.568
Not at all.

167
00:07:05.592 --> 00:07:07.236
I mean. when you get to know me.

168
00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:09.372
you'll see that I'm a
pretty good humanitarian.

169
00:07:09.396 --> 00:07:12.375
You are doing a
wonderful job. by the way.

170
00:07:12.399 --> 00:07:13.543
Thanks a lot.

171
00:07:13.567 --> 00:07:15.512
Right? Am I right? Yeah.

172
00:07:15.536 --> 00:07:17.179
Kramer.

173
00:07:17.203 --> 00:07:19.738
Kramer. come here. look
at my new friend Kevin.

174
00:07:22.075 --> 00:07:23.853
Oh. you got a little. uh...

175
00:07:23.877 --> 00:07:25.722
You got... Wha...? Oh. yeah.

176
00:07:25.746 --> 00:07:28.691
I just had. uh. two
double-fudge sundaes.

177
00:07:28.715 --> 00:07:30.527
Oh. are you all right?

178
00:07:30.551 --> 00:07:31.751
Yeah. I'll be okay.

179
00:07:33.253 --> 00:07:36.933
You know. Jerry has one of those
every time he bombs on stage.

180
00:07:36.957 --> 00:07:39.368
Well. I'm sure he'll be
sharing his next one with Pam.

181
00:07:39.392 --> 00:07:40.937
Oh. no. that won't last.

182
00:07:40.961 --> 00:07:41.938
What do you mean?

183
00:07:41.962 --> 00:07:42.962
He's not gaga.

184
00:07:50.871 --> 00:07:52.749
Let me tell you something.
That Jerry Lewis?

185
00:07:52.773 --> 00:07:54.551
You wonder how these
people get to the top?

186
00:07:54.575 --> 00:07:57.053
It's ideas like this.
Brilliant! Ha. ha.

187
00:07:57.077 --> 00:07:59.756
Look at this. What
the hell happened?

188
00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:02.300
The whole side is damaged here.

189
00:08:03.249 --> 00:08:05.027
And the lock is broken.

190
00:08:05.051 --> 00:08:06.395
How long did you leave it there?

191
00:08:06.419 --> 00:08:07.430
Five minutes.

192
00:08:07.454 --> 00:08:08.965
What the hell happened here?

193
00:08:08.989 --> 00:08:11.634
Play the tape.
Maybe we'll get a clue.

194
00:08:11.658 --> 00:08:13.803
I have to rewind it first.

195
00:08:32.546 --> 00:08:34.323
All right. All right.

196
00:08:34.347 --> 00:08:36.993
<i>Did anyone notice
George's fingernails?</i>

197
00:08:37.017 --> 00:08:39.028
<i>Oh. my. yes.</i>

198
00:08:39.052 --> 00:08:41.664
<i>They look like they were
eaten away by weevils.</i>

199
00:08:41.688 --> 00:08:44.528
<i>It's getting warm in
here. Open the window.</i>

200
00:08:45.559 --> 00:08:47.336
<i>Hey. what are you doing?</i>

201
00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:49.171
<i>Dear God!</i>

202
00:08:53.066 --> 00:08:54.443
Is that it?

203
00:08:54.467 --> 00:08:56.445
It stopped dead.

204
00:08:56.469 --> 00:08:57.680
What do you make of it?

205
00:08:57.704 --> 00:08:59.270
I don't know.

206
00:09:00.807 --> 00:09:01.784
Jerry.

207
00:09:01.808 --> 00:09:03.452
uh. can we talk?

208
00:09:03.476 --> 00:09:04.854
Kind of busy here.

209
00:09:04.878 --> 00:09:06.623
I'd like to talk to
Jerry in private.

210
00:09:06.647 --> 00:09:08.224
Why can't I stay?

211
00:09:08.248 --> 00:09:10.026
Because it doesn't concern you.

212
00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.984
Well. if it doesn't concern
me. then I can stay.

213
00:09:22.495 --> 00:09:23.640
So. what's on your mind?

214
00:09:23.664 --> 00:09:24.807
It's Pam.

215
00:09:24.831 --> 00:09:25.975
Pam? What about Pam?

216
00:09:25.999 --> 00:09:27.209
I love her. Jerry.

217
00:09:27.233 --> 00:09:28.477
You what?

218
00:09:28.501 --> 00:09:29.746
I love her.

219
00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:30.813
Is that right?

220
00:09:30.837 --> 00:09:33.215
Oh. she's... She's real.

221
00:09:33.239 --> 00:09:36.853
She can bring home the
bacon and fry it in the pan.

222
00:09:36.877 --> 00:09:38.054
What does that mean?

223
00:09:38.078 --> 00:09:40.723
Oh. and that voice.

224
00:09:40.747 --> 00:09:42.625
What about her name? Pam?

225
00:09:42.649 --> 00:09:44.248
Oh. it's a beautiful name.

226
00:09:45.151 --> 00:09:46.151
Pam.

227
00:09:47.253 --> 00:09:48.253
Pam?

228
00:09:49.556 --> 00:09:51.668
Pam!

229
00:09:51.692 --> 00:09:53.269
She's got really nice hair.

230
00:09:53.293 --> 00:09:54.470
Oh. it's incredible.

231
00:09:54.494 --> 00:09:56.639
Although. I might
replace her tortoise clip

232
00:09:56.663 --> 00:09:58.240
with one of those
velvet scrunchies.

233
00:09:58.264 --> 00:09:59.508
I love those.

234
00:09:59.532 --> 00:10:01.377
You've got really
specific tastes.

235
00:10:01.401 --> 00:10:02.946
Oh. I know what I want. Jerry.

236
00:10:02.970 --> 00:10:04.747
She's got nice calves.

237
00:10:04.771 --> 00:10:08.551
Oh. she's a dreamboat.
but you don't like her.

238
00:10:08.575 --> 00:10:10.753
Maybe I could. You're
making some good points.

239
00:10:10.777 --> 00:10:12.021
No. you can't. Jerry.

240
00:10:12.045 --> 00:10:13.022
But I might.

241
00:10:13.046 --> 00:10:14.490
Oh. no. you don't. Why not?

242
00:10:14.514 --> 00:10:16.258
The voice. the
calves. the bacon.

243
00:10:16.282 --> 00:10:19.428
What? I think I can. I
even like the name. Pam.

244
00:10:19.452 --> 00:10:21.052
Huh? Huh? Pam. Pam.

245
00:10:32.966 --> 00:10:34.777
So now he wants
her more than ever.

246
00:10:34.801 --> 00:10:36.167
Blast!

247
00:10:37.303 --> 00:10:38.781
What am I gonna do. huh?

248
00:10:38.805 --> 00:10:40.783
Don't despair. my friend.

249
00:10:40.807 --> 00:10:42.447
Ow!

250
00:10:43.844 --> 00:10:46.455
I won't allow your
love to go unrequited.

251
00:10:46.479 --> 00:10:48.224
not like mine.

252
00:10:48.248 --> 00:10:49.792
What. again with you?

253
00:10:49.816 --> 00:10:51.193
Sorry.

254
00:10:51.217 --> 00:10:54.263
But love is a spice
with many tastes.

255
00:10:54.287 --> 00:10:58.256
A dizzying array of
textures and moments.

256
00:10:59.693 --> 00:11:02.571
If only I could say things
like that around her.

257
00:11:02.595 --> 00:11:04.907
Yes.

258
00:11:06.166 --> 00:11:08.244
Well. I hear three
distinct sounds.

259
00:11:08.268 --> 00:11:10.246
A low rumple.

260
00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:13.016
followed by a metallic squink...

261
00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:15.018
Yes. yes. I heard the squink.

262
00:11:15.042 --> 00:11:19.088
Followed by a
mysterious... galonk.

263
00:11:19.112 --> 00:11:21.924
It's a real baffler. isn't it?

264
